<p class="article-lead">Good perfume sample feedback tells the perfumer where the fragrance departs from the brief and what must not be lost during revision.</p><p>Evaluate coded samples at consistent intervals. Separate opening, heart and dry-down comments. Instead of “not luxurious,” write what you perceive: too sharp in the first ten minutes, sweetness hides the floral center, or the woody dry-down should be drier.</p><h2>Consolidate before replying</h2><p>Collect internal reactions, then appoint one decision-maker to resolve contradictions. Rank changes and avoid adding new references every round. Confirm the sample code, intended concentration and product format.</p><p>A useful revision request might say: “Keep the soft musk dry-down; reduce the syrupy fruit in the opening and make the floral center clearer.” That protects the successful part while defining a testable change.</p>
